Layers of Spring:
Client request something to server-->Server has below 3 annotations
1: Controller:
2: Service
3: Repository


Client (Browser / Mobile / Postman)
        ↓
Controller Layer
        ↓
Service Layer
        ↓
Repository / DAO Layer
        ↓
Database

1. Controller Layer (Presentation Layer)
Purpose:    Handles HTTP requests
Accepts input & returns response
No business logic
Annotations
@RestController
@Controller
@RequestMapping
@GetMapping, @PostMapping

-----------------------------------------------------Example for RestController and it's methods
package Controller;

import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.PostMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@RestController    // Controller + Response body
@RequestMapping("/api")
public class ControllerClass {
	
	@GetMapping(path="/Get")
	public String getMethod() {
		System.out.println("GetMapping");
		return "Fetching data";
		
	}
	@PostMapping(path="/Post")
		String postMethod() {
			System.out.println("Posttt");
			return "PostMapping";
		
	}
	}


package Controller;
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.context.ConfigurableApplicationContext;

@SpringBootApplication
public class ControllerApp {

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		// TODO Auto-generated method stub
		ConfigurableApplicationContext context = SpringApplication.run(ControllerApp.class, args);
		ControllerClass obj = context.getBean(ControllerClass.class);

	}
}

In the browser brows with: http://localhost:9091/api/Get        //To get the GetMethod
http://localhost:9091/api/Post    // To get Post method
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
   ---   Request param

package Controller;

import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.PostMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestParam;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@RestController    // Controller + Response body
@RequestMapping("/api")
public class ControllerClass {
	
	
	
	@GetMapping(value = "/GetUser")
	public String getUserData(@RequestParam(name="firstname", required = true)String firstname,
			@RequestParam(name="lastname",required = false )String lastname, 
			@RequestParam(name="age")int age) {
				String output = "Getting user data 1st name: " + firstname +"    last name: "+ lastname +"   age: "+ age;
				return output;
		
	}




    ----- Path parameter
package Controller;

import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.PostMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestParam;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

import jakarta.websocket.server.PathParam;

@RestController    // Controller + Response body
@RequestMapping("/api")
public class ControllerClass {
	
	
	@GetMapping(path = "Pathpar/{firstname}")
	String pathparameter(@PathParam(value = "firstname")String firstname) {
		String out="firstname is::: "+firstname;
		return out;
	}



















2. Service/BusinessLayer: (this is the place where we can write a steps for data base)
we can perform CRUD operations here
Purpose:
Contains business logic
Key points:
Applies rules & validations
Calls DAO/Repository layer
Transaction management
Annotations used:
@Service

3. Repository Layer (DAO / Persistence Layer)
Purpose:
Handles database operations

Key points:
CRUD operations
No business logic
Communicates with DB
Annotations used:
@Repository
JpaRepository, CrudRepository
